"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1133201","Home Office","false","2019-06-27","<p>Each Chief Constable has a duty to manage and support their workforce effectively, ensuring the welfare of all officers and staff.</p><p>The Government takes the issue of police welfare very seriously and has invested in programmes which offer help directly to officers and staff. In July 2017 the Home Office awarded £7.5 million from the Police Transformation Fund to the College of Policing over three years to pilot and, if these pilots were successful, roll out a dedicated national service to help provide enhanced welfare support to serving police officers and staff.</p><p>Following two years of development and piloting, the National Police Wellbeing Service (NPWS) was launched in April 2019. The NPWS has developed evidence-based guidance, advice, tools and resources which can be accessed by forces, as well as individual officers and staff.</p><p>The NPWS will help forces to improve the mental health support they provide to their officers and staff, including following violent incidents.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2019-06-27T14:45:07.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1133201/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1133201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1133201/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-06-19","Police: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what mental health support his Department provides to police officers who have responded to a violent incident.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","266738"
